rlier age in both countries and that, as the populations age, baby boomers in the United States will face diminishing financial resources as the ratio of retirees to workers sharply increases. The result of a joint venture between the National Bureau of Economic Research and the Japan Center for Economic Research, this book complements Housing Markets in the United States and Japan (1994) by integrating research on housing markets with economic issues of the aged in the United States and Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aOlder people -- Housing -- Japan -- Congresses. 0aOlder people -- Housing -- United States -- Congresses. 0aOlder people -- Japan -- Economic conditions -- Congresses. 0aOlder people -- Japan -- Social conditions -- Congresses. 0aOlder people -- United States -- Economic conditions -- Congresses. 0aOlder people -- United States -- Social conditions -- Congresses. 0aOlder people. 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaging, economics, health care, social security, federal budget, elderly, housing equity, retirement, labor force participation, employment, pension, savings, wealth, baby boomers, insolvency, reform, government, japan, finance, asset holdings, household, nonfiction, politics, senior citizens, poverty, policy, ira, workforce, economy.1 aGarber, Alan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurd, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLumsdaine, Robin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcFadden, Daniel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoguchi, Yukio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoguchi, Yukio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOgura, Sei